legacy of a
revolution and the deep wounds,
but often

45:54.518 --> 45:57.321 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
strong bonds forged by war.

45:57.355 --> 46:00.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLIOT ACKERMAN, Author, "Green
on Blue":
Five years ago this past
December, the Arab

46:00.424 --> 46:05.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Spring started when a Tunisian
street vendor,
Mohamed Bouazizi, poured a can
of gasoline

46:05.696 --> 46:08.332 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over his head and lit himself on
fire.

46:08.366 --> 46:13.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was protesting a corrupt
government official's
seizure of his fruit cart and
scales. In the

46:13.437 --> 46:18.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
months that followed across
Egypt, Libya,
Yemen, and, most disastrously,
Syria, revolution

46:18.576 --> 46:20.378 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
spread.

46:20.411 --> 46:25.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, there is no revolution
left in the
Arab world, only war. Yet, the
revolutionaries

46:25.182 --> 46:30.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
remain. They are particularly
prevalent among
Syria's growing diaspora. When
the Arab Spring

46:31.022 --> 46:36.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
began, I was in Afghanistan on
my last deployment,
ending combat service that had
started in

46:36.060 --> 46:37.795 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Iraq seven years before.

46:37.828 --> 46:42.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And instead of returning home, I
returned
to the Middle East, writing
about the conflict

46:42.233 --> 46:47.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Syria from Turkey's southern
border. Working
as a journalist, I believed at
first that

46:47.538 --> 46:52.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my experience as a Marine in
America's unpopular
wars would prove a liability
when speaking

46:52.977 --> 46:55.079 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to former revolutionaries.

46:55.112 --> 47:00.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Slowly, thanks to close Syrian
friends, what
I found was quite the opposite.
A bond existed

47:00.451 --> 47:06.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
between us. And this surprised
me. One of
these friends was Abed, an
activist from Damascus

47:06.357 --> 47:08.225 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
now living in Southern Turkey.

47:08.259 --> 47:13.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Proud as Abed was of his role as
an organizer
in the 2011 protests, he felt
deeply conflicted

47:13.964 --> 47:19.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about his participation. Abed
believed in
the revolution's ideals. He
still did, yet

47:19.370 --> 47:24.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he couldn't deny that the very
forces of change
he helped unleash created a
power vacuum exploited

47:24.909 --> 47:27.945 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by extremists like the Islamic
State.

47:27.978 --> 47:32.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sipping tea or having dinner on
any given
night, Abed would begin by
asserting that

47:32.316 --> 47:37.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the revolution wasn't over,
that, despite
setbacks, hope still existed for
democracy

47:37.088 --> 47:42.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inside Syria. But by the time
each evening
drew to a close, he would often
despair: "I

47:42.827 --> 47:47.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wish we had never taken to the
streets. I
have destroyed my home."

47:47.198 --> 47:52.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Abed's inability to reconcile
what his revolution
hoped to achieve with its
outcome felt familiar

47:52.169 --> 47:57.174 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to me. When it comes to
America's wars in
Iraq and Afghanistan, I feel
almost exactly

47:57.208 --> 47:58.943 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the same conflict.

47:58.976 --> 48:03.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In addition to rooting out
al-Qaida and the
Taliban in Afghanistan, and
searching for

48:03.280 --> 48:09.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WMD in Iraq, our nation sent me
and countless
others who volunteered to bring
freedoms and

48:09.286 --> 48:13.958 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
democracy to those who had lived
under violent,
autocratic regimes for decades.

48:13.991 --> 48:20.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, it seems naive to say now,
but that was
one of the goals then. Just as
the Syrian

48:20.364 --> 48:25.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
revolution resulted in a power
vacuum filled
by international jihadists, so,
too, did the

48:25.369 --> 48:28.706 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
U.S.-led wars in Iraq and
Afghanistan.

48:28.739 --> 48:33.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As my friendship with Abed grew,
we began
to speak about the parallel
trajectories of

48:33.244 --> 48:38.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
our disillusionment, how
high-minded ideals
bogged down in the quagmire of
Islamist dogma

48:38.282 --> 48:41.318 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and sectarian bloodshed.

48:41.352 --> 48:46.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After I had known Abed for about
a year, he
invited me to his wedding. The
summer before

48:46.157 --> 48:51.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the revolution, he had met a
Swiss woman,
a university student studying in
Damascus.

48:51.295 --> 48:56.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They would be married just
outside Geneva
at the Abbey Debeve (ph) along
the banks of

48:56.400 --> 48:58.169 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
